<rss version="2.0"><channel><title>守护者</title><description>卫报全文RSS。获取更多全文RSS：https://feedx.net</description><link/> https://theguardian.com <item><title><![CDATA[‘Symbol of hope’: Lahaina’s beloved banyan shows new growth after fires]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/sep/18/lahaina-banyan-tree-hawaii-wildfires-new-growth]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-19T05:00:49Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/aa172dce661a7d4b0451e892693347217c9ab1c2/0_0_6000_4000 /master/6000.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=b120b88c3641eb8fef03f1031a2f0d86&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;拉海纳镇中心的一棵 150 年树龄的榕树在去年被烧焦后出现了新的生长迹象&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;拉海纳镇中心一棵巨大的、受人喜爱的、已有 150 年历史的榕树，上个月致命的野火肆虐夏威夷毛伊岛时被烧焦，现在却显示出新生长的绿色迹象。&lt; /p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;相关：&lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/sep/15/hawaii-fires-death-toll -update-dna-testing-missing&quot;>;夏威夷火灾：DNA 测试有助于识别受害者，死亡人数降至 97 人&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;这棵树被描述为“ &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/aug/10/lahaina-banyan-tree-burned-hawaii-wildfire&quot;>;拉海纳镇的心跳&lt;/a>;”被严重烧焦，但在上个月的大火造成至少 97 人死亡并将这座历史名镇的大部分地区化为灰烬之后，它仍然屹立不倒。 guim.co.uk/918d30c06cb80ffe84e72f583fe9efe02ed38f27/0_0_4200_2800/1000.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;2023 年 8 月 11 日，一名男子坐在因野火受损的历史悠久的榕树上。&quot; width=&quot;1000&quot; height=&quot;667&quot;>; &lt;figcaption>; &lt;span>;这棵猛犸树是印度传教士的礼物，于 1873 年种植。&lt;/span>; &lt;span>;摄影：Rick Bowmer/AP&lt;/span>; &lt;/根据夏威夷土地和自然资源部 (DLNR) 的说法，从那时起，树艺师就自愿投入时间和专业知识来拯救这棵树，并建议从这棵树烧焦的树枝上长出新叶子。复苏的积极迹象。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“对我来说，这是希望的象征。我们牢记在心，努力让这棵树回归，给拉海纳带来一些希望。”景观承包商 Chris Imonti &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.hawaiimagazine.com/a-ray-of-hope- the-lahaina-banyan-tree/&quot;>;告诉&lt;/a>; &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/2023/08/31/3-weeks-after-lahaina-wildfire-towns-famed-本月早些时候，banyan-tree-sees-hopeful-signs-life/&quot;>;记者&lt;/a>;看到他和其他人小心翼翼地为树周围的土壤通气并补充养分。 “我们不知道接下来会发生什么，但我认为这对每个人来说都将是一个新的开始。”&lt;/p>; &lt;figure data-canonical-url=&quot;https://vimeo.com/864251878&quot;>; &lt; iframe height=&quot;960&quot; width=&quot;1920&quot; src=&quot;https://player.vimeo.com/video/864251878?app_id=122963&amp;amp;dnt=true&amp;amp;dnt=true&quot;frameborder=&quot;0&quot;allowfullscreen>;&lt;/iframe >; &lt;figcaption>; 志愿者已经在树的根部浇了数千加仑的水，并正在采集根部样本来测量树的健康状况。 &lt;/figcaption>; &lt;/figure>; &lt;p>;Imoti 和其他志愿者在树根上浇了数千加仑的水，并正在采集根部样本来测量树的健康状况。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;这棵猛犸树是一棵印度传教士的礼物。它于 1873 年种植，比夏威夷群岛被宣布为美国领土早了四分之一个世纪。对于几代人来说，它一直是一个珍贵的地标，为社区活动和庆祝活动提供遮蔽。在火灾发生之前，该镇庆祝了榕树的&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.mauinews.com/news/local-news/2023/04/birthday-party-to-mark-iconic-lahaina-banyan-trees -150周年/&quot;>;150岁生日&lt;/a>;与蛋糕。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;现在，城镇的大部分地区已被大火夷为平地，数千名流离失所的居民一直住在酒店和度假屋里。官员表示，将提供为期 18 个月的租金援助，重建城镇的道路可能会很漫长。&lt;/p>; &lt;figure data-media-id=&quot;47831e24c8d26b0f4c86676afb070f6eacd3ef0e&quot;>; &lt;img src=&quot;https://media .guim.co.uk/47831e24c8d26b0f4c86676afb070f6eacd3ef0e/0_0_5184_3456/1000.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;毛伊岛野火前的榕树。&quot; width=&quot;1000&quot; height=&quot;667&quot;>; &lt;figcaption>; &lt;span>;毛伊岛野火前的榕树。&lt;/span>; &lt;span>;摄影：robertharding/Alamy&lt;/span>; &lt;/figcaption>; &lt;/figure>; &lt; p>;上周，美国能源部长詹妮弗·格兰霍姆参观了拉海纳的残骸，那里的团队仍在寻找失踪人员。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“拉海纳的榕树代表了这个社区的深厚根基。即使面对难以言喻的心痛，它的四肢也会向外、向上伸出，”她在社交媒体上写道。 “很荣幸能够见证毛伊岛人民的重建、恢复以及向外和向上的发展。”&lt;/p>;&lt;br>;&lt;hr>;&lt;div>;获取更多RSS：&lt;br>;&lt;a href=&quot;https: //feedx.net&quot; style=&quot;color:orange&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>;https://feedx.net&lt;/a>; &lt;br>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://feedx.best&quot; style=&quot;color :orange&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>;https://feedx.best&lt;/a>;&lt;br>;&lt;/div>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 19 Sep 2023 13:22:02 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Australia now in El Niño climate pattern, increasing bushfire risk, BOM says]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2023/sep/19/australia-el-nino-declaration-bom-bushfire-risk-summer-weather-temperature]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-19T05:01:20Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/28c7f424acc70f071f90694cc61647b57b4207d2/0_173_5184_3110 /master/5184.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=d942dd8e6c4e84e52a3ce60040732436&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;澳大利亚现在正处于厄尔尼诺气候模式的控制之下&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;气象局已宣布澳大利亚目前正处于厄尔尼诺气候模式，这将增加夏季炎热干燥的可能性，并增加危险的丛林火灾的风险。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;该声明是在 &lt;a href=&quot;https:/ /www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2023/sep/19/nsw-schools-close-heatwave-australia-high-fire-danger-total-fire-bans&quot;>;气温飙升和极端火灾危险&lt;/a>;横跨澳大利亚东南部部分地区。周二，新南威尔士州南海岸和大悉尼地区宣布全面禁火，而&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2023/sep/17/residents-of-queensland -towns-emerald-and-beerwah-told-evacuate-as-bushfire-approaches&quot;>;本周昆士兰部分地区发布了丛林火灾疏散令&lt;/a>;。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;联合国气象机构，世界气象组织 (WMO)，&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/jul/04/climate-heating-el-nino-has-arrived-and-threatens-lives-声明-un&quot;>;继美国国家海洋和大气管理局 (NOAA) 于 6 月宣布厄尔尼诺现象发生后，于 7 月宣布出现厄尔尼诺现象。&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;相关： &lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/jul/09/el-nino-what-does-it-mean-for-australia-and-are-more-heatwaves -and-bushfires-inevitable&quot;>;厄尔尼诺现象：这对澳大利亚意味着什么 - 更多的热浪和丛林大火是否不可避免？&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;BoM 让澳大利亚面临厄尔尼诺现象自 5 月份以来就一直发出警报，称该系统有 70% 的可能性在夏季之前锁定​​到位。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;但直到周二，澳大利亚气象局才宣布这一消息，指出缺乏具体信息。大气中的故事迹象。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;厄尔尼诺现象的特点是赤道太平洋中部地区的海面温度高于平均水平。这些温度足以让 WMO 和 NOAA 宣布气候模式已经到位。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;但 BoM 表示，大气层并未对更高的温度做出反应。在厄尔尼诺现象中，太平洋上空自东向西吹的信风减弱甚至逆转。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/jul/ 09/el-nino-what-does-it-it-mean-for-australia-and-are-more-heatwaves-and-bushfires-invitable&quot;>;气候和丛林大火专家表示&lt;/a>;厄尔尼诺现象将增加发生危险丛林大火的风险。&lt;/p>; &lt;ul>; &lt;li>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/email-newsletters?CMP=copyembed&quot; >;注册澳大利亚卫报免费的上午和下午电子邮件通讯，获取每日新闻摘要&lt;/a>;&lt;/strong>;&lt;/p>;&lt;/li>; &lt;/ul>; &lt;p>;厄尔尼诺现象往往会导致气温高于平均水平横跨澳大利亚南部大部分地区。对于澳大利亚东部，有记录以来 10 个最干燥的冬春季节中有 9 个发生在厄尔尼诺年期间。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;BoM 还确认印度洋偶极子 (IOD) 正事件正在进行中。 IOD 由东印度洋和西印度洋之间的海面温度差异决定。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;正 IOD 通常会导致澳大利亚中部和东南部春季降雨量减少。这种气候现象通常开始于深秋或冬季。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;据气象局称，厄尔尼诺年过后，澳大利亚东南部发生重大火灾危险季节的风险显着升高，特别是与厄尔尼诺现象相结合时。正 IOD。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;澳大利亚前三个夏季出现了三次拉尼娜现象，即厄尔尼诺-南方涛动的较凉爽和湿润阶段。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;这些条件促进了大量草的生长以及可能成为火灾燃料的植被生长。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;澳大利亚消防局理事会&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2023/aug/23/australian- bushfire-season-how-to-prepare&quot;>;已发布春季展望&lt;/a>;，显示昆士兰州和新南威尔士州大部分地区以及维多利亚州和北领地部分地区发生丛林火灾的风险增加。&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 19 Sep 2023 13:22:02 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Mutilating the tree of life’: Wildlife loss accelerating, scientists warn]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/sep/19/mutilating-the-tree-of-life-wildlife-loss-accelerating-scientists-warn]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-19T05:00:49Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/15faab629b41725b19e09045034fae75ff070e1a/184_161_5070_3044 /master/5070.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=37e3a35e243640577debcaabbdeb8f34&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;树上的北穆里基&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;动物物种群体正在以 35 倍的速度消失研究人员称，由于人类活动，这一物种的灭绝速度高于平均水平，这进一步证明地球历史上第六次大规模灭绝正在发生，而且正在加速。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;科学家正在分析密切相关的动物物种灭绝的速度。过去 500 年来灭绝的物种发现，如果没有人类，它们需要 18,000 年才能消失，而且它们消失的速度正在增加。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;a href=&quot;https:/ /www.pnas.org/cgi/doi/10.1073/pnas.2306987120&quot;>;发表在《美国国家科学院院刊》杂志上的研究&lt;/a>;发现，至少 73 种哺乳动物、鸟类、爬行动物和两栖动物物种分组自 1500 年以来已经灭绝。他们估计，如果趋势遵循人类出现前的平均灭绝影响率，预计只有两种会消失。消失的鸟类包括马达加斯加的象鸟、新西兰的恐鸟和夏威夷莫霍吸蜜鸟。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;由于栖息地破坏、气候危机和野生动物非法贸易，预计未来几年损失将会加速。在最坏的情况下——所有目前濒临灭绝的物种群体到本世纪末都会消失——这一速度将比过去百万年平均水平高出 354 倍。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;这项新研究的重点是“属” ”，“属”的复数形式。物种组被称为属，是物种之上的分类学分类。例如，马和斑马属于同一属，狗、狼和土狼也属于同一属。作者预计属的灭绝率低于单个物种的灭绝率。他们发现它们很相似。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;之前对化石记录的研究估计，在人类的影响之前，每个世纪就会有近万分之一的属消失。该论文称，由于已知脊椎动物约有 5,400 种（不包括鱼类），如果按照这个速度，预计每 250 年就会有一个属灭绝。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;作者 Gerardo Ceballos 教授和 Paul Ehrlich 教授，&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2015/jun/19/ humans-creating-sixth-great-extinction-of-animal-species-say-scientists&quot;>;之前已经发现该物种正在以类似于灭绝恐龙的事件的规模灭绝，并警告这种损失对人类文明的持续存在构成威胁。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;虽然声称第六次大规模灭绝一些科学家对此提出争议，&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.ipbes.net/global-assessment&quot;>;2019 年联合国对地球健康的评估&lt;/a>;发现 100 万物种面临风险由于人类对环境的压力而消失。&lt;/p>; &lt;figure data-media-id=&quot;c992af3ea965032c749fb8fa01ea521fe6062c51&quot;>; &lt;img src=&quot;https://media.guim.co.uk/c992af3ea965032c749fb8fa01ea521fe6062c51/0_0_1435_ 798/1000.jpg &quot; alt=&quot;小头鼠海豚，墨西哥附近太平洋的一种极度濒危物种。&quot; width=&quot;1000&quot; height=&quot;556&quot;>; &lt;figcaption>; &lt;span>;小头鼠海豚，墨西哥附近太平洋中的一种极度濒危物种。&lt;/span>; &lt;span>;摄影：Paula Olson/AP&lt;/span>; &lt; /figcaption>; &lt;/figure>; &lt;p>;“这种对生命之树的毁坏以及由此导致的生物多样性为人类提供的生态系统服务的丧失，对文明的稳定构成了严重威胁。研究发现，如果我们要防止这些物种灭绝及其社会影响，就必须立即采取前所未有规模的政治、经济和社会努力。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;墨西哥国立自治大学的 Ceballos 教授，他领导了这项研究。该研究告诉《卫报》，结果比他预期的要糟糕，但他表示仍有时间采取行动。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“失去所有这些属，我们正在失去地球上存在生命的基础。一般生活，特别是人类生活。如果你有一堵砖墙，如果失去一些，它不会倒塌，但不会那么坚固。如果你失去了很多砖块，最终它就会倒塌。大气中的气体组合使我们能够在地球上生存，这取决于植物、动物和生物体。人们说我们说我们预计会崩溃，这是危言耸听。我们之所以危言耸听，是因为我们感到震惊。”他说。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“尽管结果引人注目，但值得一提的是，我们还有时间。机会之窗正在迅速关闭。有希望，但我们需要迅速采取行动，”他补充道。&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;相关：&lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/environment/ 2023/aug/01/wolves-declared-extinct-in-andalucia-spain-aoe&quot;>;“可耻的损失”：安达卢西亚的狼被宣布灭绝&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;本·加罗德 (Ben Garrod)，东安格利亚大学进化生物学和科学参与教授（不是合著者）表示，这项研究是一个严厉的警告。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“所有自然——包括我们自己的物种——都遵循这个框架。 ——坚持正处于严重危险之中。由于一系列物种和物种群体的灭绝率远高于我们通常的预期，很难理解为什么全球政府、领先企业和公众没有尽一切可能来减轻这种毁灭性的损失，”他&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“灭绝是不可逆转的，”他补充道。 “从更以人类为中心的角度来看，几乎不可能预测哪些损失会对我们自己的物种产生重大影响。这是一场存在主义的赌博，我们在采取之前应该认真考虑一下。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;em>;查找更多&lt;a href=&quot;x-gu://front/mobile.guardianapis.com/international/fronts/environment /series/the-age-of-extinction&quot;>;灭绝年龄报道&lt;/a>;，并关注生物多样性记者&lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/phoeb0?lang=en&quot;>;Phoebe Weston&lt;/ a>; 和 &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/pgreenfielduk?lang=en&quot;>;Patrick Greenfield&lt;/a>; 在 &lt;/em>;&lt;em>;X 上了解所有最新新闻和功能&lt;/em>;&lt; /p>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 19 Sep 2023 13:22:02 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Russia-Ukraine war live: ‘major’ fire at Lviv warehouse after attack, Ukraine says; Zelenskiy questions Russia’s place at UN]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2023/sep/19/russia-ukraine-war-live-updates-major-fire-lviv-warehouse-attack-zelenskiy-questions-russias-place-at-un]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-19T04:51:37Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/ef2d930643a1903d8192b29c04a643e70ea2c50f/0_0_5428_3257 /master/5428.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=db87648bbe8ac59282ce5dfe4b1a2fe7&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;Volodymyr Zelenskiy（左）在纽约一家医院与受伤的乌克兰士兵。&lt;/div>;&lt;br>;&lt; hr>;&lt;div>;获取更多RSS：&lt;br>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://feedx.net&quot; style=&quot;color:orange&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>;https://feedx.net&lt;/a>; &lt;br>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://feedx.best&quot; style=&quot;color:orange&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>;https://feedx.best&lt;/a>;&lt;br>;&lt;/div>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 19 Sep 2023 12:52:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Former aide says Trump wrote to-do lists on classified documents – report]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/sep/18/former-aide-donald-trump-to-do-lists-classified-documents]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-18T23:01:42Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/5bce287c8d9b0b2eae93f1ff56fbb38e905888aa/247_502_2935_1762 /master/2935.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=17615c57a130163c99009ddcb4ea41e0&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;前总统唐纳德·特朗普在任期间，2017 年 2 月 23 日在白宫椭圆形办公室。&lt;/ div>;&lt;p>;周一有报道称，前总统的一位长期助手告诉联邦调查人员，他反复在白宫标记为机密的文件上为她写下待办事项清单，之后唐纳德·特朗普否认有不当行为。&lt;/p >; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;相关：&lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/sep/18/trump-biden-age-election-2024 ”“认知障碍”？特朗普对拜登的混乱攻击开始适得其反&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;助手莫莉·迈克尔(Molly Michael)告诉调查人员，她不止一次收到特朗普写在便条卡背面的要求或任务，她后来被认定为敏感的白宫材料，美国广播公司新闻 &lt;a href=&quot;https://abcnews.go.com/US/trump-wrote-lists-assistant-white-house-documents-marked/story?id=103226113&quot;>;周一报道&lt;/a>;，援引消息人士的话说。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;新闻媒体称，这些记录卡上有明显的分类标记，用于向特朗普在任期间通报与外国领导人的通话或其他国际事务。 &lt;/p>; &lt;p>;迈克尔于2018年成为特朗普在白宫的行政助理，并在他卸任后继续为他工作。美国广播公司新闻称，在特朗普涉嫌拒绝遵守联邦要求后，她于去年辞职。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;特朗普发言人将该报告斥为“非法泄密”，并否认有不当行为。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>; >;特朗普目前是 2024 年共和党总统提名的领跑者，&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/jun/08/trump-mar-a-lago-case-explainer&quot; >;已被指控&lt;/a>;与两名助手非法&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/jun/08/donald-trump-charged-retention-classified-documents &quot;>;在他的个人住所储存大量机密文件&lt;/a>;，并向试图取回这些文件的联邦调查人员撒谎。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;特朗普在 6 月份的一份起诉书中被指控犯有刑事罪，包括违反间谍活动采取行动、串谋妨碍司法公正以及向调查人员作出虚假陈述。他不认罪。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;特朗普还受到单独起诉&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/aug/03/trump-court-indictment- jack-smith-jan-6&quot;>;在华盛顿&lt;/a>;，&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/sep/07/donald-trump-georgia-election-指控-联邦法院&quot;>;和佐治亚州&lt;/a>;，指控他试图扭转2020年大选输给美国总统乔·拜登的局面，并在纽约向一名色情明星支付封口费。他&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/aug/31/trump-pleads-not-guilty-georgia-case-election-2020&quot;>;否认&lt;/a>;有不当行为。 &lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 19 Sep 2023 12:22:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Boris Johnson called his allies ‘The Munsters’, new book alleges]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2023/sep/19/boris-johnson-called-his-allies-the-munsters-new-book-alleges]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-19T04:00:49Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/9145b046c53895ae1903ff2e137454672344a2c8/0_141_4199_2519 /master/4199.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=34d688c8cc9252242164f469a415af9e&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;鲍里斯·约翰逊 - 在聚光灯下，在黑色背景下打手势 - 在伯明翰保守党家庭会议上发表脱欧演讲， 2018 年 10 月&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;鲍里斯·约翰逊 (Boris Johnson) 将他的政治盟友描述为“&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/film/2021/jun/16/eddie-munster-and-me-the-据称，在他因特蕾莎·梅提议的脱欧协议辞去外交大臣职务后，他经常在讨论他们时哼着《亚当斯一家》的主题曲。 &lt;/p>; &lt;p>;据《每日电讯报》政治杂志出版的一本书中称，这位于 2018 年 7 月重返保守党后座的前首相还开玩笑说，他在支持者中“垄断了性害虫市场”。编辑本·赖利-史密斯 (Ben Riley-Smith)。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;约翰逊办公室否认了这些所谓的言论，在他去年 7 月辞去首相职务之前，在强大的下议院联络委员会议员们的最后质询中提到了这些言论。未能否认他曾说过：“所有的性害虫都在支持我。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;约翰逊最终因处理一系列丑闻而被迫辞职 - 包括与前保守党议员克里斯·平彻 (Chris Pincher) 的争吵，亲密盟友，&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2023/sep/07/chris-pincher-to-resign-as-mp-after-losing-appeal-against-suspension &quot;>;本月早些时候，由于去年夏天在私人会员俱乐部对两名男子猥亵两名男子而被禁赛八周，上诉失败后，本月早些时候退出议会。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;这本书《统治的权利》 ，描述了约翰逊作为后座议员中的一个孤立人物，未能建立起坚实的支持基础，如何在私下“严厉”批评那些支持他的议员的能力。&lt;/p>; &lt;figure data-media- id=&quot;bd68444c97bbb00ba5317869e9e72e52d86478e0&quot;>; &lt;img src=&quot;https://media.guim.co.uk/bd68444c97bbb00ba5317869e9e72e52d86478e0/0_0_1809_1085/1000.jpg&quot; alt ＝《亚当斯一家》——原版电视剧，1964 年，黑白photo&quot; width=&quot;1000&quot; height=&quot;600&quot;>; &lt;figcaption>; &lt;span>;亚当斯一家 – 如原版电视剧，1964 年。&lt;/span>; &lt;span>;照片：Allstar Picture Library Limited/Alamy&lt;/span >; &lt;/figcaption>; &lt;/figure>; &lt;p>;“他们是政治边角料——正如约翰逊开玩笑的那样，‘蒙斯特一家’，指的是以弗兰肯斯坦和其他畸形食尸鬼为主角的电视节目，”莱利-史密斯写道。 “根据两个消息来源，在讨论这些问题时，他甚至哼着《亚当斯一家》的主题曲：‘嘟嘟嘟，咔嗒咔嗒，嘟嘟嘟嘟，咔嗒咔嗒’。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“有时幽默感更加黑暗。据一位消息人士透露，他曾经开玩笑说，“我已经垄断了性害虫市场”。两位没有听到具体言论的领导竞选人士提供了背景证据——其中一位说这就像约翰逊开的那种随机的、散弹枪的笑话；另一位说这就像约翰逊开的那种随机的、散弹枪的笑话；另一位说这就像约翰逊开的那种随机的、散弹枪的笑话；另一位说这就像约翰逊开的那种随机的、散弹的笑话。另一个人自发地发表了几乎相同的评论，表明这种幽默在该群体中并不罕见。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;约翰逊的 &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2021/apr/24 /key-boris-johnson-aide-lord-udny-lister-leaves-no-10&quot;>;前幕僚长爱德华·李斯特&lt;/a>;，后来被授予贵族爵位，他描述约翰逊并不是一个非常“”热衷于俱乐部的男人：“他不会在下议院的酒吧或茶室里待上几个小时，他不会那样做。他在国会议员中没有真正的朋友。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;该书还声称，约翰逊在其第一份预算之前试图忽视预算责任办公室的财政预测，该预算原定于 2019 年底，但因选举而推迟。后来的举动由莉兹·特拉斯（Liz Truss）在 &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2022/nov/12/revealed-the-30bn-cost-of-liz-trusss-disastrous-mini-budget&quot; 之前反映出来>;她灾难性的迷你预算&lt;/a>;。&lt;/p>; &lt;figure data-media-id=&quot;b110feb65ad6db615e5a034c6604f6e8f5041efe&quot;>; &lt;img src=&quot;https://media.guim.co.uk/b110feb65ad6db615e5a034c6604f6e8f5041efe/0_169_ 2539_1523/1000。 jpg&quot; alt=&quot;萨吉德·贾维德和鲍里斯·约翰逊并排坐在下议院的长凳上，贾维德的目光远离约翰逊&quot; width=&quot;1000&quot; height=&quot;600&quot;>; &lt;figcaption>; &lt;span>;鲍里斯·约翰逊的提案该书声称，在他的第一份预算之前忽视 OBR 的预测，导致他与时任财政大臣萨吉德·贾维德（左）的关系破裂。&lt;/span>; &lt;span>;照片：杰西卡·泰勒/英国议会/法新社/盖蒂图片社&lt;该书称，该提案导致约翰逊与其第一任财政大臣萨吉德·贾维德的关系破裂。唐宁街希望利用这个时机来表明紧缩政策的结束，但贾维德告诉他，如果税收不能为支出增加提供资金，那么他们就需要借款来填补公共财政的缺口。他的观点得到了 OBR 分析的支持。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“约翰逊和他的高级顾问多米尼克·卡明斯 (Dominic Cummings) 提出了一个引人注目的建议：为什么不直接进行 OBR 预测呢？这个想法是首相本人在最近一次讨论该计划的会议上提出的。 “我们就不能不理会 OBR 吗？”莱利-史密斯写道：“约翰逊询问了贾维德。”书中称，这一请求在一次会议上被贾维德“断然拒绝”。书中称，十号人物随后想要放弃保守党的财政规则，但贾维德告诉他，这将是一场“绝对的灾难”，并开始试图说服约翰逊。约翰逊办公室否认了这两项指控。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;BBC 纪录片中的另一项指控表明，高级政府官员与白金汉宫交谈，表达了对约翰逊在任期间行为的担忧，并讨论了&lt;a href=&quot;https://www. theguardian.com/politics/2023/sep/18/no-10-officials-discussed-asking-queen-to-talk-to-boris-johnson-about-his-behaviour&quot;>;要求伊丽莎白女王提出担忧&lt;/a >; 在私人接见期间与他在一起。&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 19 Sep 2023 12:22:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Zelenskiy vows to be heard as he prepares for first in-person UN address since Russia’s invasion]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/19/volodymyr-zelenskiy-un-address-speech-tuesday]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-19T02:29:31Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/1f6e064683c5198b1b8aa2aba586f4a243e6f5bc/0_0_3500_2333 /master/3500.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=7fb7de4d4f83b997eb4081afbbee3308&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;乌克兰总统弗拉基米尔·泽连斯基周一在联合国大会演讲之前访问了纽约史泰登岛大学医院。&lt; /div>;&lt;p>;弗拉基米尔·泽连斯基将于周二亲自在联合国大会上发表讲话，这是自 2022 年 2 月俄罗斯入侵以来的首次，他告诉记者：“对我们来说，非常重要的是，我们所有的言论、所有的信息都将”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;乌克兰总统在访问史泰登岛大学医院时发表了上述言论，乌克兰士兵在那里接受截肢治疗。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;2022 年，泽连斯基发送了&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2022/sep/21/joe-biden-putin-nuclear-weapons-ukraine-un-general- assembly&quot;>;在联合国的预录演讲&lt; /a>; 他在其中说道：“我们可以将乌克兰国旗归还到我们的整个领土上。我们可以用武力做到这一点，但我们需要时间。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;泽伦斯基周三还将出席联合国安理会有关乌克兰问题的会议，但不清楚他是否会继续出席 15 日的会议。如果俄罗斯外交部长谢尔盖·拉夫罗夫讲话，成员机构的马蹄形桌子。&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;相关：&lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/ film/2023/sep/18/sean-penn-interview-film-volodymyr-zelenskiy&quot;>;“他为这一刻而生”：西恩·潘谈他与泽连斯基的电影&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt; “如果联合国仍然……有俄罗斯恐怖分子的一席之地，我认为这个问题不是我的问题，而是联合国所有会员国的问题，”他说。 “我不确定我们会选择哪种形式。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;当被问及是否会留在房间里听时，泽伦斯基说，“我真的不知道会怎样。”&lt; /p>; &lt;p>;周一，乌克兰总统抵达纽约后从机场直奔医院，为受伤士兵和部分医院工作人员颁发奖章。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“感谢你们继续坚持为我们的国家而战并保卫其边界。我还要感谢医生和所有自全面战争开始以来一直支持乌克兰士兵的人，”根据总统办公室的一份声明，他说。 “我们将等待你们所有人。我们需要你们——乌克兰的每一位战士——来击败敌人。感谢您的服务！每个人都为你感到骄傲！我祝愿你们康复、胜利并回家！”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;在周二的讲话中，泽连斯基预计将向世界和华盛顿阐明自己的观点，请求华盛顿在战争已近 19 个月后继续帮助击退俄罗斯的入侵。乌克兰的西方盟友提供了武器和其他援助，美国国会正在考虑乔·拜登总统提出的再提供多达 240 亿美元军事和人道主义援助的请求。美国立法者在向乌克兰提供额外资金问题上的分歧越来越大。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;俄罗斯驻联合国大使瓦西里·内本齐亚 (Vassily Nebenzia) 上周表示，阿尔巴尼亚作为 9 月份总统召集的安理会会议将只是一场“大秀”。&lt; /p>; &lt;p>;外交正在进行&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/18/ukraine-troops-recapture-klishchiivka-village-near-bakhmut-says-zelenskiy ”乌克兰在争夺激烈的巴赫穆特市周围取得了巨大进展，重新夺回了具有重要战略意义的克里什奇夫卡村，这将标志着基辅在三天内取得的第二次重大反攻胜利。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;泽连斯基说在周日的夜间视频讲话中：“今天，我要特别赞扬那些正在一步步将属于乌克兰的东西归还给乌克兰的士兵，即巴赫穆特地区。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;巴西总统巴西总统办公室周一表示，路易斯·伊纳西奥·卢拉·达席尔瓦也将于周三在纽约会见泽连斯基。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;卢拉主张成立一个国家集团来调解结束两国之间的战争。俄罗斯和乌克兰，但五月他表示莫斯科和基辅都应对这场冲突负责，激怒了支持乌克兰抵抗俄罗斯入侵的美国和欧洲国家。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;泽连斯基预计将寻求说服卢拉表示，&lt;a href=&quot;x-gu://list/mobile.guardianapis.com/international/lists/tag/world/ukraine&quot;>;乌克兰战争&lt;/a>;并不是世界贫困人口进步的障碍，乌克兰的命运是世界的合法问题，而不仅仅是欧洲。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;上个月，这位巴西左翼领导人告诉记者，泽连斯基和俄罗斯总统弗拉基米尔·普京都没有做好和平准备。&lt;/p>; &lt;图 data-media-id=&quot;b274e313e41470fff0e4224a6f19f7d6e21b4cb0&quot;>; &lt;img src=&quot;https://media.guim.co.uk/b274e313e41470fff0e4224a6f19f7d6e21b4cb0/0_0_3409_2273/100 0.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;弗拉基米尔·泽连斯基会见一名在美国接受治疗的乌克兰士兵因战争受伤。” width=&quot;1000&quot; height=&quot;667&quot;>; &lt;figcaption>; &lt;span>;弗拉基米尔·泽连斯基会见一名因战争受伤而在美国接受治疗的乌克兰士兵。&lt;/span>; &lt;span>;照片：Eduardo Muñoz/Reuters&lt;/span>; &lt; /figcaption>; &lt;/figure>; &lt;p>;卢拉和泽连斯基从未见过面，尽管他们在三月份巴西投票支持一项呼吁和平并要求莫斯科撤军的联合国决议几天后进行了视频通话。&lt;/p>; &lt;p >;乌克兰政府要求泽连斯基和卢拉举行会面，因为两人没有在今年早些时候于日本广岛举行的七国集团峰会上会面。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;总统乔·拜登定于周四接待泽连斯基乌克兰领导人预计将在华盛顿期间会见两个政党的国会领导人。 Republican House speaker Kevin McCarthy said on Monday he would meet Zelenskiy this week.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;In a post on Telegram, Zelenskiy said he also plans to meet military and business officials.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;em>;With Reuters and Associated Press&lt;/em>;&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 19 Sep 2023 10:52:02 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Beijing summons German ambassador after foreign minister calls Xi Jinping a ‘dictator’]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/19/china-summons-german-ambassador-after-foreign-minister-calls-xi-jinping-dictator]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-19T01:14:08Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/52a17e4f65eca8fdc0289cf1ca977b5d57d34011/0_86_4500_2701/master/4500.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=089d230bdca8d6da8ed54f1f7803f80a&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;German Foreign Minister Annalena Baerbock.&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;Beijing has summoned the German ambassador to China after foreign minister Annalena Baerbock called president Xi Jinping a “dictator”, Berlin has said, in the latest flare-up of tensions between the countries.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;While they are major trade partners, Berlin-Beijing ties have been fraying as some in the German government take a harder line over issues ranging from human rights to Taiwan.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Baerbock, who has &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/apr/14/germany-annalena-baerbock-warns-horror-scenario-taiwan-strait-china&quot;>;pushed for a more hawkish line&lt;/a>;, made the remarks in a Fox News interview on Thursday during a visit to the US.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;While talking about the Ukraine war, she said: “If Putin were to win this war, what sign would that be for other dictators in the world, like Xi, like the Chinese president? So therefore Ukraine has to win this war.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;A foreign ministry spokesman in Berlin confirmed to AFP that Germany&#39;s ambassador “was summoned to the Chinese foreign ministry [on Sunday]“ in relation to the remarks.&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;Related: &lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/feb/23/germany-and-china-clash-over-wests-supply-of-weapons-to-ukraine&quot;>;Germany and China clash over west&#39;s supply of weapons to Ukraine&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;The confirmation that China summoned ambassador Patricia Flor came after China said earlier Monday that it was “strongly dissatisfied” with Baerbock&#39;s remarks.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“[The comments] are extremely absurd and are a serious infringement of China&#39;s political dignity and an open political provocation,” foreign ministry spokeswoman Mao Ning said at a daily news conference.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;In June, Beijing &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/jun/23/china-reportedly-rebukes-us-ambassador-after-biden-called-xi-a-dictator&quot;>;reportedly reprimanded the US ambassador to China&lt;/a>; after president Joe Biden also referred to Xi as a “dictator”.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Asked about China&#39;s protests over her remarks during a visit to New York, Baerbock replied only that she had “taken note” of them.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;A government spokesman refused to comment on what chancellor Olaf Scholz&#39;s view was about the remarks.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;But the spokesman added that it was clear “that China is ruled by a Communist, one-party regime, and it is also clear that this does not correspond to our idea of a democracy”.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Sunday was the third recent occasion that China has summoned Germany&#39;s ambassador.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Beijing also did so after Germany&#39;s education minister visited Taiwan in March, the first cabinet-level German visit to the island in 26 years.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Beijing claims Taiwan as its own territory to be seized one day, and has been ramping up pressure on the self-ruled, democratic island.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;In addition, the German envoy was called in following a G7 foreign ministers&#39; statement about Taiwan in August 2022, when Germany was holding the presidency of the group.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Germany is taking a harder line against China, and in July published a new policy against a more “assertive” China after &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2022/nov/03/germany-olaf-scholz-china-visit-questions-over-strategy&quot;>;months of wrangling within the government over its strategy&lt;/a>;.&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;Related: &lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/16/facing-dependence-on-china-eu-battles-to-support-green-industry&quot;>;&#39;We are facing dependence on China&#39;: EU battles to support green industry&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;It marks a fine balance between the two differing positions in its coalition government, calling Beijing a “partner, competitor, systemic rival”.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Baerbock, from the Green party, has called for a tougher stance and for a greater emphasis on human rights, while Scholz, a Social Democrat, has backed a more trade-friendly stance.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;There are also growing concerns in Berlin about potentially risky Chinese investments at home and German businesses&#39; heavy reliance on doing business in China.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Earlier this week, a source confirmed Germany had blocked a complete Chinese takeover of a satellite startup aimed at rivalling Starlink on national security grounds.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Last year, the government blocked the sale of two chipmakers to Chinese investors due to security concerns.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The proposed sale of a stake in Hamburg port to a Chinese firm sparked a furious political row, but Scholz ultimately approved the acquisition of a stake, albeit at a reduced size.&lt;/p>;&lt;br>;&lt;hr>;&lt;div>;获取更多RSS：&lt;br>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://feedx.net&quot; style=&quot;color:orange&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>;https://feedx.net&lt;/a>; &lt;br>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://feedx.best&quot; style=&quot;color:orange&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>;https://feedx.best&lt;/a>;&lt;br>;&lt;/div>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 19 Sep 2023 09:52:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[European governments shrinking railways in favour of road-building, report finds]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/19/european-governments-railways-road-building-report-motorways-funding-rail]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-19T00:01:42Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/397ea85db66e4863274122e074600a807bf36566/0_0_4989_2993/master/4989.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=0dc6ecbe9472d80758635b0fd1187588&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;Attendants wait on the platform as an Austrian Federal Railways Nightjet sleeper train is prepared for departure from the main station in Vienna.&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;European governments have “systematically” shrunk their railways and starved them of funding while pouring money into expanding their road network, &lt;a href=&quot;https://greenpeace.at/uploads/2023/09/analysis_development-of-transport-infrastructure-in-europe_2023.pdf&quot;>;a report&lt;/a>; has found.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The length of motorways in Europe grew 60% between 1995 and 2020 while railways shrank 6.5%, according to research from the German thinktanks &lt;a href=&quot;https://wupperinst.org/en/&quot;>;Wuppertal Institute&lt;/a>; and &lt;a href=&quot;https://t3-forschung.de/en/&quot;>;T3 Transportation&lt;/a>;. For every €1 governments spent building railways, they spent €1.6 building roads.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“This is a political choice,” said Lorelei Limousin, a climate campaigner with Greenpeace, which commissioned the report. “We see the consequences today with the climate, but also with people who have been left without an alternative solution to cars.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The report found the EU, Norway, Switzerland and the UK spent €1.5tn (£1.29tn) between 1995 and 2018 to extend their roads – but just €0.93tn (£0.8tn) to extend their rail networks.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;In the four years that followed (2018-21), the average gap in investment in rail and road decreased from 66% to 34%. During that time, seven countries invested more in rail than roads – Austria, Belgium, Denmark, France, Italy, Luxembourg and the UK – while the rest spent more on roads than rail.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Dr Giulio Mattioli, a transport researcher at the Technical University of Dortmund, who was not involved in the study, said: “Most European countries have been actually encouraging car use by investing large amounts of public money into expanding motorway infrastructure.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;In the public and political debate, Mattioli added, small investments into bike lanes and railways were heavily scrutinised while investments in roads were taken for granted. “This absolutely needs to change if we are to meet climate mitigation targets in the transport sector.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The report found motorways grew most in Ireland, Romania and Poland, and least in Lithuania, Latvia and Belgium. In 15 of the 30 countries studied, the lengths of motorways more than doubled over the 25-year period.&lt;/p>; &lt;figure data-media-id=&quot;fffc6e1e219042aa7e1f4cb294c615aa302d5389&quot;>; &lt;img src=&quot;https://media.guim.co.uk/fffc6e1e219042aa7e1f4cb294c615aa302d5389/0_290_4368_2621/1000.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;Weeds growing on a disused railway line with rusty railway tracks&quot; width=&quot;1000&quot; height=&quot;600&quot;>; &lt;figcaption>; &lt;span>;European governments have closed about 8,523 miles of regional passenger railway lines since the mid-90s, the study claims.&lt;/span>; &lt;span>;Photograph: Graham Turner/the Guardian&lt;/span>; &lt;/figcaption>; &lt;/figure>; &lt;p>;At the same time, the report found, European governments had shut down more than 2,500 train stations since the mid-90s. They also closed about 8,523 miles (13,717 km) of regional passenger railway lines. As a rough estimation, the researchers said, 4536 miles of these lines could be reopened “relatively easily”.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The EU plans to cut its greenhouse gas emissions by 55% by the end of the decade from 1990 levels but has failed to make any headway in its transport sector. Road transport was responsible for three-quarters of the sector&#39;s emissions in 2020. Only in 2029 will domestic transport emissions drop below 1990 levels, the European Environment Agency &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.eea.europa.eu/ims/greenhouse-gas-emissions-from-transport&quot;>;found&lt;/a>; last year. Emissions will continue to rise from planes and ships that travel between the EU and other parts of the world.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Greenpeace called on governments to move money away from roads and towards railways, public transport, cycle lanes and pavements. It also demanded an end to all new motorways and airports.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Limousin said: “To help people shift from cars to public transport, which is really key to cut the emissions of transport, we need to make the infrastructure fit for that challenge. We need the government to stop closing train lines and stations, reopen those which have been closed and that we can easily reopen … and massively increase the public funding in real solutions.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;A handful of European countries have &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/07/france-to-launch-german-style-cut-price-monthly-rail-pass&quot;>;introduced cheaper public transport tickets&lt;/a>; to encourage people to shift from cars to trains, trams and buses. In Germany last summer, the government &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2022/jul/18/germany-faces-calls-extend-9-month-public-transport-ticket&quot;>;introduced a €9-a-month ticket&lt;/a>; for local and regional public transport, which it later &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2022/nov/03/row-over-germanys-public-transport-ticket-jumping-from-9-to-49&quot;>;raised to €49 a month&lt;/a>;.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Mattioli said: “The €9 and €49 German tickets have given many the impression that people would shift to public transport if it were cheaper. But levels of service and infrastructure networks are much more important for modal shift. So I think we should be talking less about fares and a lot more about infrastructure.”&lt;/p>;&lt;br>;&lt;hr>;&lt;div>;获取更多RSS：&lt;br>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://feedx.net&quot; style=&quot;color:orange&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>;https://feedx.net&lt;/a>; &lt;br>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://feedx.best&quot; style=&quot;color:orange&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>;https://feedx.best&lt;/a>;&lt;br>;&lt;/div>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 19 Sep 2023 08:52:02 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Authorities locate debris of F-35 fighter jet that crashed in South Carolina]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/sep/18/us-stealth-f-35-fighter-jet-crash-south-carolina-update]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-19T00:23:20Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/bcf79e89cf8b1acc78aad3cd71ef1fdf73b43041/0_0_3000_2000/master/3000.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=dc55122a024e0bb4db5975007f13ea7c&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;The Marine Corps announced Monday it was pausing operations for two days after the fighter jet&#39;s crash.&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;Authorities found a debris field Monday from a Marine Corps F-35 stealth fighter jet that crashed in South Carolina after the pilot ejected and parachuted to safety.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The debris field was located in rural Williamsburg county, according to the Marine Corps&#39; Joint Base Charleston. The field is about two hours north-east of the base, and residents were being asked to avoid the area while the recovery team worked to secure it.&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;Related: &lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/sep/18/missing-f-35b-lighting-ii-fighter-jet-us-military-help-marine-corps-pilot-ejects&quot;>;US military asks for help to find missing F-35 fighter jet after &#39;mishap&#39; sees pilot eject&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;Authorities had been searching for the jet since the pilot, whose name hasn&#39;t been released, parachuted to safety into a North Charleston neighborhood about 2pm Sunday. He was taken to a hospital, where he was in stable condition, Marines Maj Melanie Salinas said.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The Marine Corps announced Monday it was pausing operations for two days after the fighter jet&#39;s crash – the third costly accident in recent weeks.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Gen Eric Smith, the acting commandant of the Marine Corps, ordered the stand-down while authorities searched near two South Carolina lakes for the missing FB-35B Lightning II aircraft.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;It&#39;s the third event documented as a “Class-A mishap” over the past six weeks, according to a Marine Corps announcement. Such incidents occur when damages reach $2.5m or more, a Department of Defense aircraft is destroyed, or someone dies or is permanently disabled.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Commanders will spend the stand-down reinforcing safe flying policies, practices and procedures with their Marines, according to the Monday release.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The announcement gave no details on the two previous incidents. But in August, three US Marines were killed in the crash of a V-22B Osprey tiltrotor aircraft during a training exercise in Australia, and a Marine Corps pilot was killed when his combat jet crashed near a San Diego base during a training flight.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Cpl Christian Cortez, a Marine with the 2nd Marine Aircraft Wing, said the search for the fighter jet in South Carolina was ongoing Monday. Exactly what happened was under investigation, he said.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Based on the missing plane&#39;s location and trajectory, the search was focused on Lake Moultrie and Lake Marion, said Senior Master Sgt Heather Stanton at Joint Base Charleston. Both lakes are north of North Charleston.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;A South Carolina law enforcement division helicopter joined the search after some bad weather cleared in the area, Stanton said. Military officials appealed in online posts Sunday for any help from the public in locating the aircraft.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The pilot of a second F-35 returned safely to Joint Base Charleston, Salinas said.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The planes and pilots were with the Marine Fighter Attack Training Squadron 501 with the 2nd Marine Aircraft Wing based in Beaufort, near the South Carolina coast.&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 19 Sep 2023 08:52:02 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Worst risk since black summer’: schools closed as early heatwave hits south-east Australia]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2023/sep/19/nsw-schools-closed-heatwave-australia-high-fire-danger-total-fire-bans]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-18T23:24:11Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/20b0c9ebca29b0f60112a7320d0733d3cf9f6098/0_76_4500_2700/master/4500.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=9dd9da2039bde7c94e7f2d1e1e94c244&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;Sun and firefighting helicopter&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;Soaring temperatures across parts of south-east Australia have resulted in high and extreme fire danger and the closure of more than 20 schools in &lt;a href=&quot;x-gu://list/mobile.guardianapis.com/international/lists/tag/australia-news/new-south-wales&quot;>;New South Wales&lt;/a>;.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Total fire bans were declared for the NSW south coast and greater Sydney region on Tuesday with temperatures forecast to reach 34C in the city.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Angus Hines from the Bureau of Meteorology said Wednesday could be even hotter with parts of South Australia and Queensland also feeling the heat.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“Most of Australia is sitting at moderate or high fire [danger] for the next few days,” he said.&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;Related: &lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2023/sep/19/very-little-has-shifted-watch-house-case-a-major-concern-for-first-nations-group-advising-queensland-police&quot;>;&#39;Very little has shifted&#39;: watch house case a major concern for First Nations group advising Queensland police&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;“The south coast of NSW has a small area of extreme fire danger there, overlapping with the heatwave conditions on Tuesday.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;It&#39;s the &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2023/sep/18/australia-weather-heatwave-temperatures-nsw-victoria-melbourne-sydney&quot;>;first total fire ban for greater Sydney since late November 2020&lt;/a>;, NSW Rural Fire Service spokesman Ben Shepherd said.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“It looks like a couple of hot and dry and windy days on the way,” he said.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Heatwave warnings are in place for Sydney, parts of the Hunter and the south coast.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The NSW education department announced 20 schools would be closed across the state&#39;s south coast on Tuesday. Parkes high school was also shut.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“Schools with elevated bushfire risk will be temporarily closed ... due to extreme fire danger ratings being declared,” the department said in a statement.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;People needed to be prepared on Tuesday, the NSW RFS commissioner, Rob Rogers, said. “It&#39;s the worst risk we&#39;ve faced since &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2023/sep/17/summer-bushfires-australia-bilpin-rural-fire-service-blue-mountains&quot;>;the black summer fires of 2019&lt;/a>;,” he said.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The heat was expected to shift north later in the week into parts of Queensland, the Northern Territory and Western Australia, with maximums of 40C forecasted.&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;Related: &lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2023/sep/19/indigenous-voice-to-parliament-referendum-no-campaign-tiktok&quot;>;No campaign spreads through TikTok &#39;like wildfire&#39; as pro-voice creators struggle to cut through&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;A severe wind warning was in place for Tuesday in the NSW Snowy Mountains and south-west slopes regions, with winds expected to become more damaging and widespread across the state on Wednesday ahead of a cold front.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Hines said the winds had emergency services on alert.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“On Wednesday, we&#39;re going to see some warm windy weather around Sydney and the Hunter, with extreme fire danger forecast in those regions.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;By Thursday, the high to extreme fire dangers would be more widespread, including a large part of the channel country in Queensland, the bureau said.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Fire crews were busy in the NSW Hunter and south-eastern parts of Queensland with a fire burning at Beerwah on the Sunshine Coast shifting between advice and watch-and-act alerts.&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 19 Sep 2023 07:52:02 +0800</pubDate></item></channel></rss>